Data analysis

fse

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict fse with age, group and time_point (formula: fse ~ 1 + age + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The models total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.68) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.15. The models intercept, corresponding to age = 0, group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 13.84 (S.E. = 2.60, p < .001, 95% CI [8.74, 18.94]). Within this model:

  • The effect of age is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.09, S.E. = 0.04, p = 0.054, 95% CI [-1.42e-03, 0.17]; Std. beta = 0.32, 95% CI [-5.35e-03, 0.65])
  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.93, S.E. = 1.29, p = 0.471, 95% CI [-3.47, 1.60]; Std. beta = -0.24, 95% CI [-0.90, 0.42])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.90, S.E. = 0.86, p = 0.295, 95% CI [-2.59, 0.78]; Std. beta = -0.23, 95% CI [-0.67, 0.20])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and positive (beta = 3.82, S.E. = 1.26, p = 0.002, 95% CI [1.34, 6.29]; Std. beta = 0.99, 95% CI [0.35, 1.63])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
